# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1884-providence-grays-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1878-providence-grays-season] The **Providence Grays** were a new franchise that joined the National League for the 1878 baseball season.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1880-providence-grays-season] The **Providence Grays** finished the 1880 season in second place in the National League.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] The **Providence Grays** went 84–28 during the 1884 season to win the National League championship.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] The team started out with two main pitchers, Charles "Old Hoss" Radbourn and Charlie Sweeney.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] After Sweeney jumped to the Union Association in mid-season, Radbourn pitched most of the Grays' remaining games and led the team to the pennant.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Radbourn won 60 games by himself, setting a Major League Baseball record that has never been broken.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] After the regular season, the Grays faced the American Association champions, the New York Metropolitans, in the 1884 World Series.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] In 1883, the Providence Grays finished in third place.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Pitcher Charles "Old Hoss" Radbourn won 48 games.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Before the 1884 season, manager Harry Wright left the team and was replaced by Frank Bancroft.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] The franchise was on shaky financial ground, and ownership was close to disbanding the team.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] In early 1884, the Grays' two main pitchers were Radbourn and Charlie Sweeney.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Both Radbourn and Sweeney were talented pitchers but also vain and temperamental.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Through much of April and May, the younger Sweeney outshone the veteran Radbourn, creating tension between the two.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] On June 7, 1884, Sweeney struck out 19 Boston batters to set the single-game MLB record.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] The record would be tied a few times but not broken for 102 years, until Roger Clemens struck out 20 in a game in 1986.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Sweeney was feted upon his return to Providence for days following his accomplishment, much to the bitter jealousy of Radbourn.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Not long after that, Sweeney suffered arm problems which sidelined him.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] This meant that Radbourn would suffer the workload of two men, further driving a wedge between the veteran and the upstart.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] The two eventually fought in the clubhouse, and on July 16, Radbourn had a meltdown on the mound, intentionally lobbing several slow pitches over the plate in a losing effort.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Sweeney was forced to return to his regular pitching duties, which he did effectively for a time.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Following an exhibition game on July 21 in Woonsocket, Rhode Island, Sweeney, who had allegedly been drinking throughout the game, refused to return with the team to Providence, choosing to stay in Woonsocket with a lady he had escorted to the park that day.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Waking the next morning, he realized he missed morning practice and raced to make it back to Providence for his start that afternoon.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Though most players at the time were held to temperance clauses during the season, Grays manager Frank Bancroft was left with little choice but to pitch Sweeney.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] After five effective innings, Bancroft signaled for the team captain Joe Start to make a pitching change.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Sweeney refused to budge and continued to pitch for another two innings.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] With the Grays leading 6–2 before the start of the eighth inning, Bancroft insisted that Sweeney vacate the pitcher's box and move to right field.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Still intoxicated, as well as the prevailing sentiment of 1880s baseball being that finishing a game a pitcher started was a question of manhood, Sweeney flatly refused.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] When Bancroft threatened the pitcher with a $50 fine, Sweeney told him to take his fine and the rest of his salary, promptly quitting.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] This left Providence with only eight players.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] With two men to cover the outfield, they lost the game.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Sweeney watched the rest of the game in street clothes and left with two women, presumably prostitutes.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] The Grays subsequently expelled Sweeney from the National League.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Louis Maroons of the Union Association, helping the Maroons win the UA's only championship.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] For the season, Sweeney pitched 221 innings for the Grays, going 17–8 with a 1.55 ERA, and pitched 271 innings for the Maroons, going 24–7 with a 1.83 ERA.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] With only one main pitcher left, the Grays were left in a state of disarray with the consensus view that the team should be disbanded.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] At that point, Radbourn, who had spent the last several weeks demanding he be paid for doing the work of two men, offered to start every game for the rest of the season (having pitched in 76 of 98 games the season before).
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] In exchange, he wanted a raise and exemption from the reserve clause for the next season.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Ownership agreed, and Radbourn got his raise.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Over the Grays' next 43 games, Radbourn started 40 of them and won 36.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Soon, pitching every other day as he was, his arm became so sore he couldn't even raise it to comb his hair.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] On game day he was at the ballpark hours before the start, getting warmed up.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] He began his warm up by throwing just a few feet, increasing the distance gradually until he was pitching from second base and finally from short center field.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Led by Radbourn, the Grays got hot and stayed hot, clinching the National League championship on September 24 and finishing the season with a record of 84–28.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Radbourn himself finished the season with a league-leading 678.2 innings pitched and 73 complete games, and he won the Triple Crown with a record of 60–12, a 1.38 earned run average, and 441 strikeouts.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] His 60 wins in a season is a record which is expected to never be broken because no pitcher has made even as many as 37 starts in a season since 1991.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Also, his 678.2 innings pitched stands at second all-time, behind only Will White (680 in 1879) for a single season.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] At the end of the season, Providence officials accepted New York Metropolitans (AA) manager Jim Mutrie's challenge to a three-game postseason match, which became known as the first World Series.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] All of the games took place at the Polo Grounds in New York and were played under American Association rules, which forbade overhand pitching.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Each team put up one thousand dollars with the winner taking all.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Radbourn allowed two hits and struck out nine, and the Grays defeated the Metropolitans, 6–0.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] New York's ace pitcher, Tim Keefe, took the loss.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] The next day, Radbourn three-hit the Metropolitans and won 3–1 in a game called after seven innings due to darkness.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Grays third baseman Jerry Denny hit a three-run home run in the fifth inning, the first homer in World Series history.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Providence had clinched the series, but New York, hoping to generate more revenue, asked them to play the third game anyway.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] The Grays agreed to play as long as they had the option of choosing the umpire, and they strategically chose Keefe, the Metropolitans' best pitcher.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Due to the extremely cold weather, the attendance for the game was just 300, and the game was called after six innings.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Radbourn, pitching his third complete game in three days, led the Grays to a 12–2 rout.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Buck Becannon was the losing pitcher for New York.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Overall, Radbourn pitched all 22 innings in the series, allowing 11 hits, three unearned runs, and no earned runs.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] The total attendance for the three games was 3,800.
[src:1884-providence-grays-season/1884-providence-grays-season] Local newspaper *The New York Clipper* called the series "The Championship of the United States." Several newspapers such as *The Sporting Life* penned the Grays as "World Champions," and the new title stuck.
